         <abstract>
            <p>This paper explores the impact of partial acquisitions on the economic benefit for the acquirer. In the case when the acquisition price is independent of the acquisition fraction, the paper shows that it is optimal to buy either a minimum share (say alpha percent that captures the synergy), or 100% of the target firm, depending on the price, but not any other fraction. In the case when the acquisition price varies with the acquisition level, it is shown that the optimum acquisition fraction can be an interior solution between alpha and 100%. It is also demonstrated that the maximum price to pay could be higher than what is normally shown in the literature.</p>
         </abstract>
